Florence is a game about growth. It focuses on the titular character and her rocky, uncertain path through life, as she seeks meaning in her mundane, ordinary life. The game itself, while it does dwell on the subject of romance, instead chooses to chart the course of Florence's life, using that relationship as one of multiple stepping stones across a gushing river of uneasiness and anxiety, until she reaches a shore of clarity and contentment with her life, looking back fondly at the past.

An existential, and honest, exploration of the love of art and romance. Hopefully a sign to come for mobile games, an absolutely incredible piece of work (even if it's a pretty basic or cliche story), the mechanics absolutely draw you in and the use of colours rivals that of triple A titles. The use of colour reminds me of Ghost of Tsushima in how well the developers have implemented it (again, even though it's by the numbers). If this is the future of mobile games, I'm excited.

This game is a beautiful, albeit short game. The quality of Florence is not something I'm accustomed to in a mobile game. The graphics are gorgeous and stylized, and the music is excellent. While the gameplay is fairly simple, the engaging, human story within more than makes up for it. There are no loot boxes, no timers, no energy meter, just a solid story that most people can relate to. While the game is a bit short, it doesn't overstay its welcome. It left me wanting more games in the vein of Florence. Florence shows just how much potential for engaging storytelling exists in the mobile market. I hope to see other developers follow in the footsteps of Annapurna Interactive and push the boundaries of mobile games.

This is a visual novel/interactive comic, and it is gorgeously made with stunning storytelling. The creative choices made in how to depict Florence and her world through the "game" mechanics is wonderful. The story is short, simple, and relatable, but to me the main charm of the game is the emotional journey Florence goes through. The game mechanics elevates this and is an integral part of the storytelling, and alongside the beautiful music it allows the viewer an emotional peek into Florence's mind. Personally, this is what I want the future of comics to be. I absolutely loved it.

large with the "puzzles." They aren't meant to be challenging, they're 
meant to convey the experience the character is having at the time. I 
delighted and cried right along with her. My only complaint is that it is 
incredibly brief; I finished it in less than an hour (half an hour?). And 
being a story, there isn't really any re-playing opportunity. But I still 
loved it and have zero regrets of buying it.

I saw this game in a game informer magazine and thought the art style was 
cute (I am a sucker for pretty much any art in this kind of style), so I 
immediately went to the Google store and got it. I tend to enjoy the story 
of visual novels but do not always like that they aren't incredibly 
interactive. So a puzzle/interactive visual novel sounded perfect for me. 
It took me about 30-45 minutes to complete this game, and while there is 
not much replay value once you know the story, there is value in it for me 
just for going through the art and mechanics again. The puzzles weren't 
really challenging, but were fun and enjoyable to complete. The story 
itself was really relatable for pretty much anyone who has been in a 
relationship that ended. The emotions it invokes without words are complex 
and beautiful. It is very well done and I definitely recommend it (:

And by the end if the story, despite how sad I was at times, I genuinely felt happy and satisfied with how it ended. Also ((SPOILERS AHEAD DONT READ IF U HAVENT FINISHED THE GAME)) that moment when it hit me, her first love was art not Krish (although he was her first romantic love), I was really happy with how her 'first love' ended up. Learning to do what makes her happy and find happiness in her life and with the people around her. I was really glad she seemed to make some new friends and spend quality time with her mom instead of only interacting with her when she calls and it feels like she's nagging. Overall I just love this story and the style, the gameplay and puzzles. I hope u guys make more games and stories in the future!

I am in love with this game! Everything from the incredible art style to the music which matches each scene perfectly. You can tell straight from the start that this is the kind of game that the app-store was made for. Even the little details such as the speech bubble puzzles getting easier as you chat more symbolising the character getting more comfortable and finding it easier to talk with the man, just show how much effort and love the developers have put into this app! One of the greats! Would definitely recommend for an experience that you rarely can find in a phone app game. Thank you.
